1
00:00:36,900 --> 00:00:38,900
<i>... and I'll tell you what,</i>
<i>the storm system's still moving west.</i>

2
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:42,000
What are you looking at, Caroline?

3
00:00:43,100 --> 00:00:44,600
The wind, Mom.

4
00:00:47,700 --> 00:00:50,100
They say the hurricane is coming.

5
00:00:51,800 --> 00:00:55,000
I'm on a boat.

6
00:00:55,100 --> 00:00:57,300
I'm drifting.

7
00:00:59,700 --> 00:01:02,000
Can I do anything for you, Mom?

8
00:01:03,300 --> 00:01:05,200
Make anything easier?

9
00:01:06,200 --> 00:01:07,600
Oh, sugar...

10
00:01:08,100 --> 00:01:10,400
There's nothing left to do.

11
00:01:10,900 --> 00:01:12,500
Is what it is.

12
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Finding it harder to keep my eyes open.

13
00:01:18,900 --> 00:01:22,100
My mouth's full of cotton.

14
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:24,700
There, there, Miss Daisy.

15
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:27,600
You gonna scratch yourself to ribbons.

16
00:01:32,500 --> 00:01:35,300
Do you want any more
medication, Mother?

17
00:01:36,200 --> 00:01:39,400
Doctor said you could have
as much as you want.

18
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:41,700
No need for anybody to suffer.

19
00:01:56,700 --> 00:01:59,600
A friend told me
that she never had the chance

20
00:01:59,700 --> 00:02:02,000
to say goodbye to her mother.

21
00:02:05,200 --> 00:02:07,500
- I wanted to...
- It's okay.

22
00:02:07,600 --> 00:02:11,100
I wanted to tell you
how much I'm gonna miss you so...

23
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:12,700
Mom.

24
00:02:14,700 --> 00:02:16,500
Oh, Caroline.

25
00:02:22,300 --> 00:02:23,800
Are you afraid?

26
00:02:23,900 --> 00:02:25,600
I'm curious.

27
00:02:27,400 --> 00:02:29,000
What comes next?

28
00:02:34,500 --> 00:02:39,300
They built the train station in 1918.

29
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:43,100
My father was there the day it opened.

30
00:02:44,700 --> 00:02:47,400
He said they had

31
00:02:49,400 --> 00:02:50,700
a tuba band playing.

32
00:02:55,500 --> 00:02:59,500
They had the finest clockmaker
in all of the South

33
00:03:00,100 --> 00:03:02,900
to build that glorious clock.

34
00:03:04,800 --> 00:03:06,400
<i>His name was...</i>

35
00:03:08,300 --> 00:03:10,100
Mr. Gateau.

36
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:15,600
Mr. Cake.

37
00:03:18,200 --> 00:03:22,300
<i>He was married to a Creole</i>
<i>of Evangeline Parish</i>

38
00:03:22,500 --> 00:03:24,700
<i>and they had a son.</i>

39
00:03:26,600 --> 00:03:31,700
<i>Mr. Gateau was, from birth,</i>
<i>absolutely blind.</i>

40
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:38,200
<i>When their son was old enough,</i>
<i>he joined the army.</i>

41
00:03:39,200 --> 00:03:43,500
<i>And they prayed God would</i>
<i>keep him out of harm's way.</i>

42
00:03:46,500 --> 00:03:51,200
<i>For months,</i>
<i>he did nothing but work on that clock.</i>

43
00:03:55,300 --> 00:03:56,700
<i>One day,</i>

44
00:03:58,100 --> 00:04:00,000
<i>a letter came.</i>

45
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:09,000
<i>And Mr. Gateau, done for the night,</i>

46
00:04:09,700 --> 00:04:12,200
<i>went up, alone, to bed.</i>

47
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:17,600
<i>And their son came home.</i>

48
00:04:22,800 --> 00:04:25,600
<i>They buried him in the family plot,</i>

49
00:04:25,700 --> 00:04:29,600
<i>where he would be with them</i>
<i>when their time came.</i>

50
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:34,700
<i>Mr. Cake worked on his clock,</i>

51
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:41,200
<i>laboring to finish.</i>

52
00:04:43,100 --> 00:04:46,400
<i>It was a morning to remember.</i>

53
00:04:47,700 --> 00:04:50,900
<i>Papa said</i>
<i>there were people everywhere.</i>

54
00:04:52,300 --> 00:04:54,900
<i>Even Teddy Roosevelt came.</i>

55
00:05:12,600 --> 00:05:14,500
It's running backwards!

56
00:05:16,100 --> 00:05:17,900
I made it that way

57
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:21,300
so that perhaps the boys
that we lost in the war

58
00:05:21,400 --> 00:05:22,800
might stand and come home again.

59
00:05:27,700 --> 00:05:29,100
<i>Home to farm,</i>

60
00:05:30,200 --> 00:05:31,400
<i>work,</i>

61
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:34,700
<i>have children.</i>

62
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,500
<i>To live long, full lives.</i>

63
00:05:43,700 --> 00:05:46,400
Perhaps my own son
might come home again.

64
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,600
I'm sorry if I've offended anybody.

65
00:05:59,100 --> 00:06:01,400
I hope you enjoy my clock.

66
00:06:02,300 --> 00:06:06,200
<i>Mr. Cake was never seen again.</i>

67
00:06:10,600 --> 00:06:15,000
<i>Some say he died of a broken heart.</i>

68
00:06:16,700 --> 00:06:19,000
<i>Some say he went to sea.</i>

69
00:06:24,100 --> 00:06:25,300
Excuse me.

70
00:06:25,400 --> 00:06:28,000
Do you mind if I make a call?
Somebody's watching my little boy.

71
00:06:28,100 --> 00:06:29,300
Sure.

72
00:06:39,500 --> 00:06:41,800
I hope I haven't disappointed you.

73
00:06:41,900 --> 00:06:45,000
You couldn't disappoint me.

74
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:51,300
Well, I know I don't have much
to show for myself.

75
00:06:53,900 --> 00:06:56,300
Find my dark suitcase.

76
00:07:00,700 --> 00:07:03,600
There's a diary.

77
00:07:05,800 --> 00:07:06,800
This?

78
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:12,500
Could you read it to me?

79
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,300
Is this what you want to do?

80
00:07:15,400 --> 00:07:19,300
I tried to read it
a hundred different times.

81
00:07:20,300 --> 00:07:22,200
Mom, it's not exactly...

82
00:07:22,400 --> 00:07:25,800
It's just the sound of your voice, darling.

83
00:07:26,400 --> 00:07:27,600
Okay.

84
00:07:30,700 --> 00:07:33,700
It's dated April 4th, 1985.

85
00:07:34,800 --> 00:07:37,200
And it says New Orleans.

86
00:07:37,300 --> 00:07:40,000
"This is my last will and testament.

87
00:07:40,100 --> 00:07:44,300
"I don't have much to leave,
few possessions, no money, really.

88
00:07:44,700 --> 00:07:49,900
"I will go out of this world the same way
I came in, alone and with nothing.

89
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:52,500
"All I have is my story,

90
00:07:52,600 --> 00:07:56,000
"and I'm writing it now
while I still remember it.

91
00:07:56,800 --> 00:08:00,000
"My name is Benjamin.
Benjamin Button."

92
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:03,400
<i>And I was born under</i>
<i>unusual circumstances.</i>

93
00:08:04,400 --> 00:08:06,600
<i>The First World War had ended,</i>

94
00:08:07,300 --> 00:08:11,200
<i>and I've been told it was</i>
<i>an especially good night to be born.</i>

95
00:08:12,800 --> 00:08:15,000
Thank God it's over!

96
00:08:15,100 --> 00:08:16,900
We won the war!

97
00:08:31,800 --> 00:08:33,600
The Great War is over!

98
00:08:45,900 --> 00:08:46,900
What are you doing here?

99
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:48,300
Thomas,

100
00:08:49,600 --> 00:08:51,000
I'm afraid she's going to die.

101
00:08:51,100 --> 00:08:52,300
What?

102
00:08:53,400 --> 00:08:57,100
That's enough.
All of you, get away from her.

103
00:09:00,300 --> 00:09:03,400
I came as quickly as I could.
The streets are filled with people.

104
00:09:03,500 --> 00:09:04,800
Thomas.

105
00:09:05,300 --> 00:09:07,900
Promise me he has a place.

106
00:09:10,300 --> 00:09:11,400
Yeah.

107
00:09:12,800 --> 00:09:14,800
<i>She gave her life for me.</i>

108
00:09:15,800 --> 00:09:18,800
<i>And for that, I am forever grateful.</i>

109
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:29,800
Mr. Button.

110
00:09:45,100 --> 00:09:46,300
Thomas!

111
00:09:46,400 --> 00:09:47,700
Thomas.

112
00:09:49,700 --> 00:09:51,800
Thomas? Where are you going?

113
00:10:20,500 --> 00:10:22,800
Hey! What are you doing there?

114
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:26,100
What do you have there?

115
00:11:23,700 --> 00:11:26,100
- Come on, Queenie.
- Now, Mr. Weathers!

116
00:11:26,200 --> 00:11:29,500
Come on, now, you know I ain't got
nothing but work to do around here.

117
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:31,900
- Come on. Just take some time.
- Stop all this foolishness.

118
00:11:35,100 --> 00:11:36,900
The air is sweet.

119
00:11:41,300 --> 00:11:44,400
You look very handsome tonight,
Miss Queenie.

120
00:11:45,700 --> 00:11:47,800
Handsome as I've ever seen.

121
00:11:49,300 --> 00:11:51,500
The brown matches your eyes.

122
00:11:51,600 --> 00:11:53,000
Oh, hush!

123
00:11:54,400 --> 00:11:58,600
Let's see here.
You ain't no slouch yourself.

124
00:12:07,100 --> 00:12:08,900
Hambert's back in town.

125
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:12,800
He came home legless, but he's home.

126
00:12:13,800 --> 00:12:16,400
I know you were sweet on him one time.

127
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:18,900
Sweeter than I should've been.

128
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:20,900
Miss Simone messed herself.

129
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:22,200
Oh, sweet Jesus.

130
00:12:22,300 --> 00:12:24,800
She got to stop doing that
or it's diapers for her.

131
00:12:24,900 --> 00:12:27,000
- I'll be right there, Miss Jameson!
- Now, Queenie, now come on.

132
00:12:27,100 --> 00:12:29,600
Okay, Queenie'll be right there.

133
00:12:29,700 --> 00:12:31,000
It's awful nice out here.

134
00:12:31,100 --> 00:12:34,300
Come on out back for a moment.
Take your mind off things.

135
00:12:34,400 --> 00:12:35,400
You're so bad.

136
00:12:35,500 --> 00:12:38,000
- What in God's name?
- What's this?

137
00:12:48,400 --> 00:12:50,600
Oh, the Lord done something here.

138
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:54,200
Hope I didn't hurt it none
stepping on it like that.

139
00:12:54,300 --> 00:12:55,800
We best leave that for the police.

140
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:57,400
Poor baby.

141
00:12:58,300 --> 00:12:59,600
I'll go.

142
00:13:00,300 --> 00:13:04,000
It's for sure nobody wanted to keep it.
Come on, baby.

143
00:13:06,600 --> 00:13:09,100
Queenie? Where are you, Queenie?

144
00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:11,100
Hold your water! You go deal with it.

145
00:13:11,200 --> 00:13:13,300
Okay. No, go, I'll be back.

146
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:17,400
Queenie, Apple, she went and messed
herself all over again!

147
00:13:17,500 --> 00:13:19,400
Jane Childress, start her a bath!

148
00:13:19,500 --> 00:13:21,600
And mind your own business,
Mrs. Duprey.

149
00:13:21,700 --> 00:13:23,500
You'll be messing yourself
soon enough.

150
00:13:23,600 --> 00:13:25,100
Somebody stole my necklace.

151
00:13:25,300 --> 00:13:28,200
Okay. All right, Mrs. Hollister,
I'll be right with you, okay?

152
00:13:28,300 --> 00:13:30,500
Go on back upstairs, hear?

153
00:13:36,800 --> 00:13:39,300
You are as ugly as an old pot

154
00:13:39,400 --> 00:13:41,100
but you're still a child of God.

155
00:13:41,200 --> 00:13:43,600
Queenie, Apple,
she won't take a bath without you!

156
00:13:43,700 --> 00:13:45,100
Mercy.

157
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:47,200
I'll be right there!

158
00:13:50,200 --> 00:13:53,200
Okay. You just wait right here
for me now, okay?

159
00:13:56,500 --> 00:14:01,100
My sister gave me those pearls.
I can't find them anywhere.

160
00:14:01,300 --> 00:14:05,100
- Somebody's been stealing my jewelry.
- They're right here, Mrs. Hollister. See?

161
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:08,500
Right around your pretty white neck.
Now, come on. Hush all that noise.

162
00:14:08,600 --> 00:14:11,200
- Is Dr. Rose still here?
- I don't know.

163
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:15,300
Your heart is strong.

164
00:14:15,400 --> 00:14:18,400
You just want to avoid
any undue stimulation.

165
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:22,100
I trust you ladies
will help me out with that?

166
00:14:22,200 --> 00:14:25,300
I have something.
Could you come downstairs?

167
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:32,700
Never seen anything like it.
Nearly blind from cataracts.

168
00:14:32,800 --> 00:14:36,900
I'm not sure if he can hear.
His bones indicate severe arthritis.

169
00:14:37,700 --> 00:14:42,100
His skin has lost all elasticity,
and his hands and feet are ossified.

170
00:14:42,200 --> 00:14:46,800
He shows all the deterioration,
the infirmities, not of a newborn,

171
00:14:46,900 --> 00:14:49,500
but of a man well in his 80s
on his way to the grave.

172
00:14:49,600 --> 00:14:50,600
He's dying?

173
00:14:50,700 --> 00:14:54,000
His body is failing him
before his life's begun.

174
00:14:56,300 --> 00:14:57,800
Where'd he come from?

175
00:14:57,900 --> 00:15:02,200
My sister's child. From Lafayette.
She had an unfortunate adventure.

176
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:06,300
The poor child, he got the worst of it.
Come out white.

177
00:15:09,300 --> 00:15:13,900
There are places for unwanted babies
like these, Queenie.

178
00:15:14,500 --> 00:15:17,200
No room for another mouth to feed here.

179
00:15:17,300 --> 00:15:19,800
The Nolan Foundation,
despite their good intentions,

180
00:15:19,900 --> 00:15:22,700
thinks this place is
a large nuisance as it is.

181
00:15:22,800 --> 00:15:22,900
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

182
00:15:22,900 --> 00:15:25,000
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

183
00:15:25,100 --> 00:15:29,600
Queenie, some creatures
aren't meant to survive.

184
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:36,800
No, this baby, he is a miracle.
That's for certain.

185
00:15:36,900 --> 00:15:39,900
Just not the kind of miracle
one hopes to see.

186
00:15:42,900 --> 00:15:45,400
Y'all listen. Y'all listen up here.

187
00:15:46,200 --> 00:15:47,200
We're gonna have us a visitor

188
00:15:47,300 --> 00:15:50,400
that's gonna be staying with us
for a little while.

189
00:15:50,500 --> 00:15:54,200
My sister had a child
and she couldn't see right by it, so...

190
00:15:56,500 --> 00:15:58,200
He's known as...

191
00:16:01,500 --> 00:16:02,800
Benjamin.

192
00:16:03,500 --> 00:16:04,800
Benjamin.

193
00:16:05,700 --> 00:16:08,600
He's not a well child, so we're gonna
have to take good care of him.

194
00:16:08,700 --> 00:16:09,800
I had 10 children.

195
00:16:09,900 --> 00:16:13,200
There's not a baby I can't care for.
Let me see him.

196
00:16:15,400 --> 00:16:19,100
God in Heaven.
He looks just like my ex-husband.

197
00:16:19,900 --> 00:16:22,500
Look, he's prematurely old.

198
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:26,600
Dr. Rose said he ain't got much more
time on this earth.

199
00:16:26,900 --> 00:16:28,000
Join the club.

200
00:16:33,100 --> 00:16:34,600
He's smiling!

201
00:16:41,400 --> 00:16:44,000
Hambert sends his
remembrances to you.

202
00:16:53,900 --> 00:16:56,200
Are you right out of your mind?

203
00:16:57,500 --> 00:17:00,900
I know you ain't got all the parts
it takes to make one of your own,

204
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:02,200
but this ain't yours to keep.

205
00:17:02,300 --> 00:17:04,600
It may not even be humankind.

206
00:17:13,700 --> 00:17:16,100
Mr. Weathers, come back here.

207
00:17:18,500 --> 00:17:19,700
Please.

208
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,600
You never know what's coming for you.

209
00:17:48,600 --> 00:17:51,000
<i>It seemed I had found a home.</i>

210
00:17:54,200 --> 00:17:55,200
Is any of this true?

211
00:17:55,300 --> 00:17:58,700
You have such a lovely voice.

212
00:17:59,300 --> 00:18:03,900
Mom, it's an ancient streetcar token.

213
00:18:05,600 --> 00:18:08,800
That clock just kept going,

214
00:18:09,800 --> 00:18:14,000
year after year after year.

215
00:18:18,300 --> 00:18:20,200
<i>But I didn't know I was a child.</i>

216
00:18:20,300 --> 00:18:22,800
Same old crap every day.

217
00:18:23,700 --> 00:18:26,400
<i>I thought I was like everyone else there.</i>

218
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:29,600
<i>An old man in the twilight of his life.</i>

219
00:18:29,700 --> 00:18:32,000
Could you make him stop that?

220
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:36,100
Stop banging that fork.
It's used for eating, not for playing with.

221
00:18:36,200 --> 00:18:39,000
And use your napkin, please,
Mr. Benjamin.

222
00:18:41,400 --> 00:18:42,700
Queenie!

223
00:18:54,800 --> 00:18:56,000
Hey, boy.

224
00:19:03,400 --> 00:19:05,700
<i>Always had a healthy curiosity.</i>

225
00:19:06,900 --> 00:19:10,400
<i>What was up the street?</i>
<i>Or around the next corner?</i>

226
00:19:12,200 --> 00:19:13,500
Go get him!

227
00:19:13,600 --> 00:19:17,300
Benjamin! That is dangerous.
Come back over here.

228
00:19:18,100 --> 00:19:19,800
Stay put, child.

229
00:19:22,200 --> 00:19:24,100
<i>I loved her very much.</i>

230
00:19:24,900 --> 00:19:26,500
<i>She was my mother.</i>

231
00:19:26,600 --> 00:19:27,800
Mama.

232
00:19:28,500 --> 00:19:29,600
Mama.

233
00:19:30,500 --> 00:19:34,200
Some days I feel different
than the day before.

234
00:19:35,700 --> 00:19:39,700
Everybody feels different about
themselves, one way or another.

235
00:19:40,700 --> 00:19:43,000
But we're all going the same way.

236
00:19:44,300 --> 00:19:48,000
Just taking different roads to get there,
that's all.

237
00:19:48,100 --> 00:19:50,600
You're on your own road, Benjamin.

238
00:19:53,300 --> 00:19:56,000
Mama? How much longer I got?

239
00:19:56,500 --> 00:19:59,800
Just be thankful
for what you're given, hear?

240
00:19:59,900 --> 00:20:03,000
You're already here longer
than you're supposed to.

241
00:20:05,900 --> 00:20:08,800
<i>Some nights, I'd have to sleep alone.</i>

242
00:20:17,500 --> 00:20:19,200
<i>I didn't mind.</i>

243
00:20:20,100 --> 00:20:22,800
<i>I would listen to the house breathing.</i>

244
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:26,100
<i>All those people sleeping.</i>

245
00:20:27,500 --> 00:20:29,700
<i>I felt safe.</i>

246
00:20:50,600 --> 00:20:53,200
<i>It was a place of great routine.</i>

247
00:20:53,300 --> 00:20:56,200
<i>Every morning at 5:30,</i>
<i>no matter the weather,</i>

248
00:20:56,300 --> 00:21:00,400
<i>General Winslow, U.S. Army, Retired,</i>
<i>would raise the flag.</i>

249
00:21:03,200 --> 00:21:07,200
<i>Mrs. Sybil Wagner,</i>
