00:37:53,100 --> 00:37:56,400
Once I was just crossing
the road to get the mail.

501
00:38:12,400 --> 00:38:13,700
<i>I never forgot her...</i>

502
00:38:13,800 --> 00:38:15,300
"...blue eyes."

503
00:38:16,800 --> 00:38:18,300
Mom?

504
00:38:18,400 --> 00:38:23,200
Did you get that this Benjamin loved you
from the first time that he saw you?

505
00:38:24,500 --> 00:38:26,900
Not many people experience that.

506
00:38:28,400 --> 00:38:30,200
Want me to go on?

507
00:38:32,200 --> 00:38:34,200
He crosses something out.

508
00:38:34,300 --> 00:38:37,600
<i>When that baby came,</i>
<i>things were different.</i>

509
00:38:37,700 --> 00:38:41,000
<i>Your mama gone away</i>
<i>And your daddy gonna stay</i>

510
00:38:41,100 --> 00:38:44,900
<i>Didn't leave nobody but the baby</i>

511
00:38:46,400 --> 00:38:49,000
<i>Babies were born, people died.</i>

512
00:38:49,900 --> 00:38:52,700
<i>A lot of folks been through</i>
<i>that old house.</i>

513
00:38:54,700 --> 00:38:57,900
I've come to say goodbye.
I'm going away.

514
00:38:58,100 --> 00:38:59,300
Going?

515
00:38:59,800 --> 00:39:01,300
Where?

516
00:39:01,500 --> 00:39:03,000
I haven't figured that out yet,

517
00:39:03,100 --> 00:39:05,600
but I'll send you a postcard
when I get there.

518
00:39:05,700 --> 00:39:08,500
What about your friend, the tall lady?

519
00:39:08,600 --> 00:39:10,000
We are not friends anymore.

520
00:39:10,100 --> 00:39:13,300
That's what happens
with tall people sometimes.

521
00:39:13,400 --> 00:39:16,200
Well, goodbye.

522
00:39:35,500 --> 00:39:38,300
<i>Spent a lot of time by myself that year.</i>

523
00:39:39,600 --> 00:39:40,900
Hello?

524
00:39:42,600 --> 00:39:44,400
- Hi.
- I'm moving in today.

525
00:39:44,500 --> 00:39:47,300
Welcome. We've been expecting you.

526
00:39:47,400 --> 00:39:50,500
Can you please show her up
to Mrs. Rousseau's old room?

527
00:39:50,600 --> 00:39:53,900
I'm sorry, but we usually
don't allow dogs in the house.

528
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:57,000
Well, she's old as the hills.
She's almost blind.

529
00:39:57,100 --> 00:40:00,000
She won't be a bother much longer.

530
00:40:00,100 --> 00:40:03,800
Well, all right,
long as she stays from up underfoot.

531
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:05,100
Right this way, ma'am.

532
00:40:05,300 --> 00:40:08,400
<i>As hard as I try,</i>
<i>I can't remember her name.</i>

533
00:40:08,500 --> 00:40:11,600
<i>Mrs. Lawson, or Mrs. Hartford.</i>

534
00:40:12,700 --> 00:40:14,400
<i>Maybe it was Maple.</i>

535
00:40:14,500 --> 00:40:16,900
<i>It's funny how sometimes</i>
<i>the people we remember the least</i>

536
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:19,500
<i>make the greatest impression on us.</i>

537
00:40:20,100 --> 00:40:22,400
<i>I do remember she wore diamonds.</i>

538
00:40:22,500 --> 00:40:26,300
<i>And she always dressed in fine</i>
<i>clothing, as if she was going out.</i>

539
00:40:26,400 --> 00:40:30,000
<i>Although she never did</i>
<i>and nobody ever came to visit her.</i>

540
00:40:31,700 --> 00:40:34,100
<i>She taught me to play the piano.</i>

541
00:40:39,500 --> 00:40:42,100
It's not about how well you play.

542
00:40:42,800 --> 00:40:45,700
It's how you feel
about what you're playing.

543
00:40:45,800 --> 00:40:47,100
Try this.

544
00:41:03,400 --> 00:41:06,700
You can't help putting yourself
in the music.

545
00:41:14,800 --> 00:41:16,700
<i>There were many changes.</i>

546
00:41:16,900 --> 00:41:19,900
<i>Some you could see,</i>
<i>some you couldn't.</i>

547
00:41:21,100 --> 00:41:23,900
<i>Hair had started growing</i>
<i>in all sorts of places,</i>

548
00:41:24,400 --> 00:41:26,400
<i>along with other things.</i>

549
00:41:27,700 --> 00:41:30,400
<i>I felt pretty good, considering.</i>

550
00:41:31,500 --> 00:41:34,200
Darling, the pain.

551
00:41:34,300 --> 00:41:36,800
All right, Mom, I'll get the nurse.

552
00:41:39,300 --> 00:41:42,000
<i>Look at this eye.</i>
<i>This is a major hurricane,</i>

553
00:41:42,600 --> 00:41:45,100
<i>a slow hurricane,</i>
<i>with maximum sustained winds of...</i>

554
00:41:45,200 --> 00:41:47,100
Not doing too good?

555
00:41:47,900 --> 00:41:51,200
Nobody seems to know
whether to stay or leave.

556
00:41:51,300 --> 00:41:53,600
I'm gonna ride it out.

557
00:41:53,700 --> 00:41:56,600
There.
That should make things much easier.

558
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:03,200
Have you had a chance
to say your goodbyes?

559
00:42:03,300 --> 00:42:06,800
My father waited four hours for
my brother to get here from Boger City.

560
00:42:06,900 --> 00:42:08,900
Couldn't go without him.

561
00:42:09,400 --> 00:42:12,100
- She seems like a sweet woman.
- Yeah.

562
00:42:12,700 --> 00:42:14,400
I haven't had as much time with her
as I would've...

563
00:42:14,500 --> 00:42:16,400
- You busy? I could use your help.
- Excuse me.

564
00:42:16,600 --> 00:42:17,800
Sure.

565
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:38,000
"Queenie would let me go
with Mr. Daws..."

566
00:42:38,100 --> 00:42:41,900
<i>... to Poverty Point to watch the boats</i>
<i>go up and down the river.</i>

567
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:43,900
<i>These were hard times.</i>

568
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:50,700
Did I ever tell you I was struck
by lightning seven times?

569
00:42:51,600 --> 00:42:55,000
Once when I was in the field,
just tending to my cows.

570
00:43:01,600 --> 00:43:03,800
My fourth hand didn't show up.

571
00:43:06,100 --> 00:43:09,500
Anybody want to make $2
for a day's work 'round here?

572
00:43:11,500 --> 00:43:13,200
What's the matter?

573
00:43:13,300 --> 00:43:16,000
Nobody wants to do an honest
day's work for an honest day's pay?

574
00:43:16,100 --> 00:43:17,700
He never pays.

575
00:43:19,100 --> 00:43:21,400
- Nobody wants a job?
- I do.

576
00:43:23,100 --> 00:43:25,900
You got your sea legs about you,
old man?

577
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:28,400
I think.

578
00:43:32,400 --> 00:43:34,800
Well, that's good enough for me.

579
00:43:34,900 --> 00:43:38,400
Get your ass on board.
We'll sure as hell find out.

580
00:43:43,900 --> 00:43:45,500
<i>I was as happy as I could be.</i>

581
00:43:45,600 --> 00:43:46,900
I need a volunteer!

582
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:48,300
<i>I would do anything.</i>

583
00:43:48,400 --> 00:43:49,800
Yes, Captain!

584
00:43:49,900 --> 00:43:52,200
Scrape off all this bird shit!

585
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:54,700
Right away, sir.

586
00:43:55,500 --> 00:44:00,000
<i>And I was actually gonna be paid</i>
<i>for something I would've done for free.</i>

587
00:44:01,700 --> 00:44:04,000
<i>His name was Captain Mike Clark.</i>

588
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:07,900
<i>He'd been on a tugboat</i>
<i>since he was seven.</i>

589
00:44:08,900 --> 00:44:10,700
Get moving, then.

590
00:44:11,600 --> 00:44:13,100
Come here.

591
00:44:15,200 --> 00:44:18,300
Can you still get it up?

592
00:44:19,600 --> 00:44:21,600
I do every morning.

593
00:44:22,300 --> 00:44:25,700
The old pole, huh? The high, hard one?

594
00:44:26,300 --> 00:44:27,600
I guess.

595
00:44:30,300 --> 00:44:32,900
When was the last time
you had a woman?

596
00:44:35,400 --> 00:44:37,300
- Never.
- Never?

597
00:44:37,800 --> 00:44:39,900
Not that I know of, sir.

598
00:44:40,400 --> 00:44:42,200
Wait a minute, now.

599
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:47,100
You mean to say you've been
on this earth however many years

600
00:44:47,200 --> 00:44:50,500
and you've never had a woman?

601
00:44:55,100 --> 00:44:58,200
Damn, that's the saddest thing
I've ever heard in my life.

602
00:44:59,700 --> 00:45:00,900
Never?

603
00:45:01,700 --> 00:45:02,800
No.

604
00:45:05,400 --> 00:45:09,500
Well, then, by Jesus,
you are coming with me.

605
00:45:20,500 --> 00:45:22,100
What did your father do?

606
00:45:22,200 --> 00:45:24,300
I never met my father.

607
00:45:24,400 --> 00:45:26,300
You lucky bastard.

608
00:45:27,200 --> 00:45:29,800
All fathers want to do is hold you down.

609
00:45:32,500 --> 00:45:35,900
Out on my father's boat,
workin' the two-a-day,

610
00:45:36,200 --> 00:45:38,700
this little, fat bastard.

611
00:45:38,800 --> 00:45:40,400
"Tug Irish," they called him.

612
00:45:40,600 --> 00:45:43,900
Anyway, I finally work up the nerve
and tell him,

613
00:45:44,800 --> 00:45:48,500
"I don't want to spend the rest of my life
on a goddamn tugboat."

614
00:45:48,600 --> 00:45:50,600
You know what I'm saying?

615
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:53,700
You don't want to spend
the rest of your life on a tugboat.

616
00:45:53,800 --> 00:45:56,100
Absolutely! Damn right!

617
00:45:58,800 --> 00:46:01,400
So you know
what my father says to me?

618
00:46:02,300 --> 00:46:06,700
He says,
"Who the hell do you think you are?

619
00:46:06,800 --> 00:46:09,500
"What the hell do you think you can do?"

620
00:46:09,900 --> 00:46:11,500
So I tell him.

621
00:46:12,200 --> 00:46:15,300
"Well, if you're asking,

622
00:46:17,600 --> 00:46:19,600
"I want to be an artist."

623
00:46:20,200 --> 00:46:22,100
He laughs.

624
00:46:22,600 --> 00:46:27,600
"An artist? God meant for you
to work a tugboat, just like me.

625
00:46:27,700 --> 00:46:30,400
"And that's exactly
what you're gonna do."

626
00:46:30,500 --> 00:46:33,700
Well, I turned myself into an artist.

627
00:46:36,200 --> 00:46:37,900
A tattoo artist!

628
00:46:40,300 --> 00:46:43,100
I put on every one of these myself.

629
00:46:45,700 --> 00:46:49,500
You have to skin me alive
to take my art away from me now.

630
00:46:50,300 --> 00:46:53,800
When I'm dead,
I'm gonna send him my arm.

631
00:46:55,100 --> 00:46:56,500
That one.

632
00:46:58,800 --> 00:47:01,400
Don't let anyone tell you different.

633
00:47:01,500 --> 00:47:04,100
You gotta do what you're meant to do.

634
00:47:04,200 --> 00:47:07,300
And I happen to be a goddamned artist.

635
00:47:07,900 --> 00:47:10,200
But you're a tugboat captain.

636
00:47:10,800 --> 00:47:12,600
Captain Mike?

637
00:47:12,700 --> 00:47:15,400
We're ready for you and your friend.

638
00:47:17,200 --> 00:47:20,200
Let's go, old timer, eh?
Break your cherry.

639
00:47:21,400 --> 00:47:24,100
- Hello, my lovelies!
- Hey, Captain.

640
00:47:24,200 --> 00:47:25,200
- Hi, Captain.
- Hi.

641
00:47:27,400 --> 00:47:28,500
- Hi.
- Hi.

642
00:47:28,600 --> 00:47:31,600
He gives me the willies.
That is not for me.

643
00:47:33,500 --> 00:47:35,800
How are you tonight, grandpa?

644
00:47:36,500 --> 00:47:38,600
<i>It was a night to remember.</i>

645
00:47:44,300 --> 00:47:48,000
What are you, Dick Tracy or something?
I've got to rest.

646
00:47:49,100 --> 00:47:50,400
Again.

647
00:47:51,700 --> 00:47:54,000
- Thank you.
- No, thank you. You have a nice night.

648
00:47:54,100 --> 00:47:56,200
- Will you be here tomorrow?
- Every night but Sunday.

649
00:47:56,400 --> 00:48:00,100
<i>It sure made me understand</i>
<i>the value of earning a living.</i>

650
00:48:00,700 --> 00:48:02,500
Good night, sweetie. Come back now.

651
00:48:02,600 --> 00:48:04,800
<i>Things money can buy you.</i>

652
00:48:22,500 --> 00:48:24,200
It's nasty out.

653
00:48:24,700 --> 00:48:27,600
Can I offer you a ride somewhere?

654
00:48:29,300 --> 00:48:31,600
Well, that's awfully kind of you, sir.

655
00:48:40,900 --> 00:48:43,400
My name is Thomas, Thomas Button.

656
00:48:44,100 --> 00:48:46,200
- I'm Benjamin.
- Benjamin.

657
00:48:47,400 --> 00:48:49,600
It's a pleasure to know you.

658
00:48:51,100 --> 00:48:54,300
Would you like to stop somewhere
and have a drink?

659
00:48:54,400 --> 00:48:55,800
All right.

660
00:48:57,100 --> 00:48:59,400
Evening, Mr. Button.

661
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:05,900
What'll it be, sir?

662
00:49:06,600 --> 00:49:09,700
- I'll have whatever he's having.
- Sazerac for the both of us.

663
00:49:09,800 --> 00:49:12,100
With whiskey, not brandy.

664
00:49:12,200 --> 00:49:13,700
You don't drink, do you?

665
00:49:13,800 --> 00:49:16,400
- It's a night for firsts.
- How's that?

666
00:49:16,500 --> 00:49:18,600
I've never been to a brothel, either.

667
00:49:18,700 --> 00:49:21,500
Well, it's an experience.

668
00:49:21,600 --> 00:49:24,700
It certainly is.
There's a time for everything.

669
00:49:24,800 --> 00:49:27,200
- True enough.
- Your drinks.

670
00:49:28,900 --> 00:49:34,100
I don't mean to be rude, but your hands.
Is that painful?

671
00:49:34,400 --> 00:49:37,000
Well, I was born
with some form of disease.

672
00:49:37,200 --> 00:49:38,700
What kind of disease?

673
00:49:38,800 --> 00:49:40,600
I was born old.

674
00:49:42,100 --> 00:49:43,800
- I'm sorry.
- No need to be.

675
00:49:43,900 --> 00:49:46,400
There's nothing wrong with old age.

676
00:49:55,300 --> 00:49:58,300
My wife passed away many years ago.

677
00:49:59,700 --> 00:50:01,600
I'm so, so sorry.

678
00:50:03,100 --> 00:50:04,900
She died in childbirth.

679
00:50:08,400 --> 00:50:10,900
- To children.
- To mothers.

680
00:50:15,800 --> 00:50:18,100
What line of work you in, Mr. Button?

681
00:50:18,200 --> 00:50:22,300
Buttons. Button's Buttons.
There isn't a button that we don't make.

682
00:50:24,500 --> 00:50:26,900
Our biggest competition
is B.F. Goodrich

683
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:28,700
and his infernal zippers.

684
00:50:28,800 --> 00:50:31,600
Would you gentlemen like
anything else?

685
00:50:31,700 --> 00:50:33,700
One for the road, Benjamin?

686
00:50:33,800 --> 00:50:36,700
Only if you let me pay for it, Mr. Button.

687
00:50:38,000 --> 00:50:40,400
So, what line of work do you do?

688
00:50:41,900 --> 00:50:44,300
I'm a tugboat man.

689
00:50:50,500 --> 00:50:52,500
I enjoyed talking to you.

690
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:55,100
I enjoyed drinking with you.

691
00:50:58,700 --> 00:51:00,100
Benjamin?

692
00:51:00,200 --> 00:51:03,700
Would you mind if, time to time,
I stopped by and said hello?

693
00:51:03,800 --> 00:51:07,200
Anytime. Good night, Mr. Button.

694
00:51:07,700 --> 00:51:09,500
Good night, Benjamin.

695
00:51:10,200 --> 00:51:11,600
Drive on.

696
00:51:17,300 --> 00:51:18,600
Where have you been?

697
00:51:18,700 --> 00:51:23,700
Nothing. I met some people
and listened to some music.

698
00:51:26,500 --> 00:51:28,700
Oh, sweet Jesus, boy!

699
00:51:29,700 --> 00:51:32,800
<i>Growing up's a funny thing.</i>
<i>Sneaks up on you.</i>

700
00:51:33,700 --> 00:51:38,000
<i>One person is there, then suddenly</i>
<i>somebody else has taken her place.</i>

701
00:51:38,600 --> 00:51:40,300
<i>She wasn't all elbows</i>
<i>and knees anymore.</i>

702
00:51:40,400 --> 00:51:42,100
Benjamin! Come on!

703
00:51:42,500 --> 00:51:43,800
Okay.

704
00:51:45,100 --> 00:51:46,700
<i>I loved those weekends</i>
<i>when she'd come</i>

705
00:51:46,800 --> 00:51:49,600
<i>and spend the night</i>
<i>with her grandmother.</i>

706
00:51:57,700 --> 00:52:00,100
Daisy. Daisy.

707
00:52:01,300 --> 00:52:03,500
You want to see something?

708
00:52:04,600 --> 00:52:09,400
You gotta keep it a secret,
so get dressed. I'll meet you out back.

709
00:52:14,900 --> 00:52:16,300
Come on.

710
00:52:18,100 --> 00:52:21,200
- Can you swim?
- I can do anything you can do.

711
00:52:21,400 --> 00:52:23,900
Here, put this on. We gotta hurry.

712
00:52:36,900 --> 00:52:38,400
Is he okay?

713
00:52:38,500 --> 00:52:40,000
Captain?

714
00:52:41,600 --> 00:52:43,100
Captain Mike?

715
00:52:46,800 --> 00:52:49,500
Morning, Captain. Can you take us out?

716
00:52:50,700 --> 00:52:53,000
Do you know what day it is?

717
00:52:53,100 --> 00:52:54,400
Sunday?

718
00:52:54,500 --> 00:52:56,600
Do you know what that means?

719
00:52:58,000 --> 00:53:00,400
Means I was very drunk last night.

720
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:03,200
Well, you're drunk every night.

721
00:53:05,700 --> 00:53:08,000
- Is that a girl?
- Close friend.

722
00:53:08,700 --> 00:53:09,800
I want to show her the river.

723
00:53:09,900 --> 00:53:13,200
You're not supposed to go joyriding
with civilians.

724
00:53:14,400 --> 00:53:16,500
I could lose my license.

725
00:53:26,300 --> 00:53:27,800
What are you waiting for?

726
00:53:58,000 --> 00:54:01,100
Pulled in for repair a wounded duck.

727
00:54:02,500 --> 00:54:04,600
She's flying now, huh?

728
00:54:05,200 --> 00:54:06,800
Ahoy, sailor!

729
00:54:11,400 --> 00:54:13,700
I wish we could go with them.

730
00:54:19,700 --> 00:54:22,000
Did you say something, Mom?

731
00:54:29,800 --> 00:54:31,800
It's getting really bad.

732
00:54:33,800 --> 00:54:35,600
Can you hear me, Mom?

733
00:54:38,200 --> 00:54:40,900
Time just seeped out of me.

734
00:54:47,600 --> 00:54:49,400
"Things were changing quickly."

735
00:54:49,500 --> 00:54:53,600
I don't know how it's possible,
but you seem to have more hair.

736
00:54:55,200 --> 00:54:58,100
What if I told you
that I wasn't getting older,

737
00:54:58,200 --> 00:55:01,500
but I was getting younger
than everybody else?

738
00:55:01,600 --> 00:55:05,600
Well, I'd feel sorry for you,

739
00:55:05,700 --> 00:55:08,500
to have to see everybody you love
die before you do.

740
00:55:08,600 --> 00:55:10,500
It's an awful responsibility.

741
00:55:10,600 --> 00:55:14,200
<i>I'd never thought about life or death</i>
<i>that way before.</i>

742
00:55:15,800 --> 00:55:19,900
Benjamin, we're meant
to lose the people we love.

743
00:55:20,300 --> 00:55:23,700
How else would we know
how important they are to us?

744
00:55:26,800 --> 00:55:31,300
<i>And one fall day, a familiar visitor</i>
<i>came knocking on our door.</i>

745
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:35,800
You want to go with me
to the drugstore?

