what you're talking about.

807
00:59:56,800 --> 01:00:00,300
The hummingbird
is not just another bird.

808
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:04,700
Its heart rate's 1,200 beats per minute.

809
01:00:06,500 --> 01:00:09,200
Its wings beat 80 times a second.

810
01:00:11,100 --> 01:00:14,100
If you was to stop their wings
from beating,

811
01:00:14,800 --> 01:00:17,600
it would be dead
in less than 10 seconds.

812
01:00:18,600 --> 01:00:21,300
This is no ordinary bird.

813
01:00:21,900 --> 01:00:24,000
This is a frickin' miracle.

814
01:00:27,200 --> 01:00:31,100
They slowed down their wings
with moving pictures,

815
01:00:31,800 --> 01:00:34,000
and you know what they saw?

816
01:00:34,500 --> 01:00:37,300
Their wingtips are doing that.

817
01:00:41,300 --> 01:00:45,200
You know what the figure eight
is the mathematical symbol for?

818
01:00:48,200 --> 01:00:49,700
Infinity.

819
01:00:49,800 --> 01:00:51,100
Infinity!

820
01:00:54,600 --> 01:00:57,500
<i>Everybody, no matter</i>
<i>what differences they had,</i>

821
01:00:57,600 --> 01:01:01,700
<i>the languages, the color of their skin,</i>
<i>had one thing in common.</i>

822
01:01:02,600 --> 01:01:05,000
<i>They were drunk every single night.</i>

823
01:01:05,100 --> 01:01:06,600
Three, please.

824
01:01:06,700 --> 01:01:08,300
Could you hold, dear, for us, please?

825
01:01:08,400 --> 01:01:10,700
Thank you very much. Good evening.

826
01:01:10,800 --> 01:01:13,500
<i>Her name was Elizabeth Abbott.</i>

827
01:01:13,600 --> 01:01:16,900
<i>She was not beautiful.</i>
<i>She was plain as paper.</i>

828
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:19,800
<i>But she was pretty as any picture to me.</i>

829
01:01:21,100 --> 01:01:23,100
What are you looking at?

830
01:01:25,400 --> 01:01:27,900
If you must know,
we have a longstanding agreement

831
01:01:28,000 --> 01:01:29,400
never to go to bed sober.

832
01:01:29,500 --> 01:01:31,900
- Isn't that right, darling?
- Whatever you say, darling.

833
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:34,000
<i>Her husband was Walter Abbott.</i>

834
01:01:34,100 --> 01:01:38,000
<i>He was Chief Minister of</i>
<i>the British Trade Mission in Murmansk,</i>

835
01:01:38,100 --> 01:01:39,800
<i>and he was a spy.</i>

836
01:01:39,900 --> 01:01:42,700
- Darling.
- Oh, thank you, my darling.

837
01:01:42,800 --> 01:01:44,900
- Key, darling.
- Oh, yes.

838
01:01:49,400 --> 01:01:52,400
I broke my heel off one of my shoes.

839
01:01:52,500 --> 01:01:56,100
I'm not in the habit of walking about
in my stocking feet.

840
01:02:00,500 --> 01:02:02,700
<i>They were long days there.</i>

841
01:02:10,200 --> 01:02:12,200
<i>And even longer nights.</i>

842
01:02:14,400 --> 01:02:17,900
<i>One particular night,</i>
<i>I was having trouble sleeping.</i>

843
01:02:19,400 --> 01:02:20,900
I'm sorry.

844
01:02:22,800 --> 01:02:24,500
I couldn't sleep.

845
01:02:37,400 --> 01:02:40,900
I was gonna make some tea.
Would you like some?

846
01:02:41,800 --> 01:02:43,600
Oh, no. Thank you.

847
01:03:21,500 --> 01:03:23,000
Milk? Honey?

848
01:03:23,700 --> 01:03:25,600
A bit of honey, please.

849
01:03:26,200 --> 01:03:27,900
I hope you like flies in your honey.

850
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:29,700
Oh, perhaps not.

851
01:03:44,500 --> 01:03:48,800
Oh, maybe better to let it steep a little.

852
01:03:49,800 --> 01:03:51,000
Steep?

853
01:03:51,300 --> 01:03:52,400
Soak.

854
01:03:52,700 --> 01:03:56,300
I don't know, I mean,
there's a proper way of making tea.

855
01:03:56,400 --> 01:03:59,700
Well, where I'm from,
people just want it to be hot.

856
01:03:59,800 --> 01:04:01,900
Well, quite right.

857
01:04:10,800 --> 01:04:13,200
- Now, you're a seaman.
- A sailor.

858
01:04:13,300 --> 01:04:16,000
I hope you won't think me impolite,
but I have to ask,

859
01:04:16,100 --> 01:04:18,300
aren't you a little old
to be working on a boat?

860
01:04:18,400 --> 01:04:21,800
There's no age limit,
as long as you can do the work.

861
01:04:32,600 --> 01:04:34,900
And you have trouble sleeping?
Thank you.

862
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:38,200
I didn't think I did.
I usually sleep like a baby.

863
01:04:39,200 --> 01:04:41,600
Something's been keeping me up.

864
01:04:42,800 --> 01:04:44,000
My father, in his 80s,

865
01:04:44,100 --> 01:04:47,400
he was so convinced
he was gonna die in his sleep,

866
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:51,200
he limited himself
to having afternoon naps.

867
01:04:51,900 --> 01:04:54,700
He was so determined
he was gonna cheat death.

868
01:04:55,900 --> 01:04:57,700
- Did he?
- Did he what?

869
01:04:57,900 --> 01:04:59,500
Die in his sleep?

870
01:05:01,200 --> 01:05:03,800
He died sitting in his favorite chair

871
01:05:03,900 --> 01:05:06,500
listening to his favorite program
on the wireless.

872
01:05:06,700 --> 01:05:09,100
He must have known something.

873
01:05:14,900 --> 01:05:19,900
My husband's the British Trade Minister,
and we've been here for 14 months.

874
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:23,400
- Good God.
- We were supposed to go to Peking

875
01:05:23,500 --> 01:05:26,900
but it never seemed to work out.

876
01:05:28,400 --> 01:05:30,100
Have you been in the Far East?

877
01:05:30,200 --> 01:05:32,400
No. I've never been anywhere, really.

878
01:05:32,500 --> 01:05:34,900
I mean, outside of harbors.

879
01:05:35,000 --> 01:05:36,700
And where is it that you're from?

880
01:05:36,800 --> 01:05:39,300
New Orleans. Louisiana.

881
01:05:40,800 --> 01:05:43,100
I didn't know there was another.

882
01:05:45,400 --> 01:05:50,500
<i>And she told me about all the places</i>
<i>she had been, and what she had seen.</i>

883
01:05:52,100 --> 01:05:55,000
<i>And we talked till just before the dawn.</i>

884
01:05:56,000 --> 01:05:57,500
I'm just a lush, myself.

885
01:05:57,600 --> 01:06:02,500
<i>And we went back to our rooms,</i>
<i>to our separate lives.</i>

886
01:06:07,900 --> 01:06:11,200
<i>But every night,</i>
<i>we'd meet again in that lobby.</i>

887
01:06:16,600 --> 01:06:20,500
<i>A hotel in the middle of the night</i>
<i>can be a magical place.</i>

888
01:06:23,400 --> 01:06:26,300
<i>A mouse running, and stopping.</i>

889
01:06:27,700 --> 01:06:29,800
<i>A radiator hissing.</i>

890
01:06:30,800 --> 01:06:32,700
<i>A curtain blowing.</i>

891
01:06:36,400 --> 01:06:39,800
<i>There's something peaceful,</i>
<i>even comforting</i>

892
01:06:39,900 --> 01:06:43,100
<i>knowing that the people you love</i>
<i>are asleep in their beds</i>

893
01:06:43,200 --> 01:06:45,500
<i>where nothing can harm them.</i>

894
01:06:48,600 --> 01:06:51,500
<i>Elizabeth and I would lose track</i>
<i>of the night</i>

895
01:06:52,100 --> 01:06:54,200
<i>until just before daybreak.</i>

896
01:06:56,800 --> 01:06:59,600
I think I may have given you
the wrong impression.

897
01:06:59,700 --> 01:07:01,300
Beg pardon?

898
01:07:01,400 --> 01:07:05,200
Well, married women don't customarily
sit around

899
01:07:05,300 --> 01:07:07,300
in the middle of the night
with strange men in hotels.

900
01:07:07,400 --> 01:07:10,900
I wouldn't know what a married woman
does or doesn't do.

901
01:07:16,700 --> 01:07:18,100
Good night.

902
01:07:20,500 --> 01:07:21,800
Murmansk.

903
01:07:24,400 --> 01:07:27,500
"I've met somebody,
and I've fallen in love."

904
01:07:27,600 --> 01:07:28,800
Mom?

905
01:07:32,600 --> 01:07:35,200
That was over 60 years ago.

906
01:07:36,500 --> 01:07:37,500
Did you love him, Mother?

907
01:07:37,600 --> 01:07:40,400
What does a girl know about love?

908
01:08:14,000 --> 01:08:15,200
Well...

909
01:08:17,700 --> 01:08:21,400
- I'm not dressed.
- Oh, you look splendid, just as you are.

910
01:08:23,700 --> 01:08:26,800
Don't waste any time bothering about
the wine or the cheese in Murmansk,

911
01:08:26,900 --> 01:08:29,900
'cause they're really
completely ordinary,

912
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:35,000
but the caviar and the vodka

913
01:08:35,600 --> 01:08:39,700
are sublime and plentiful.

914
01:08:43,500 --> 01:08:44,700
So.

915
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:51,300
Savor it.

916
01:08:53,500 --> 01:08:55,400
And don't eat it all at once,

917
01:08:55,500 --> 01:08:58,600
