regarding your future,

977
01:15:00,600 --> 01:15:02,200
possibly beyond.

978
01:15:03,600 --> 01:15:06,100
There's been a change of plan, lads.

979
01:15:06,400 --> 01:15:08,900
As you may or may not know,

980
01:15:09,100 --> 01:15:11,600
the Japs bombed
Pearl Harbor yesterday.

981
01:15:12,100 --> 01:15:15,500
Frank D. Roosevelt's asked
each of us to do our part.

982
01:15:16,100 --> 01:15:20,200
The <i>Chelsea's</i> been commissioned
to serve in the United States Navy.

983
01:15:20,600 --> 01:15:23,900
To repair, to salvage, and to rescue.

984
01:15:25,400 --> 01:15:29,700
Anybody doesn't want to go to war,
now is the time to say so.

985
01:15:29,800 --> 01:15:34,000
Once you set foot on that boat,
you're in the Navy, friend.

986
01:15:37,300 --> 01:15:40,300
Yeah, I've been meaning
to talk with you, Mike.

987
01:15:40,400 --> 01:15:42,400
My wife's doing poorly.

988
01:15:42,500 --> 01:15:45,300
I'd like to maybe see her one more time.

989
01:15:47,000 --> 01:15:50,800
You're free to make your way home
any way you can, Mr. Mayes.

990
01:15:56,400 --> 01:15:58,200
Well, if he's leaving, who's gonna cook?

991
01:15:58,300 --> 01:16:02,400
Food poisoning's one of the leading
causes of death at sea.

992
01:16:02,500 --> 01:16:04,800
Right after
inadequate safety equipment.

993
01:16:04,900 --> 01:16:07,600
I can cook, Captain.
Been doing it all my life.

994
01:16:07,700 --> 01:16:12,100
I don't know.
You're a little moody for war, Benjamin.

995
01:16:12,200 --> 01:16:14,200
What the hell?

996
01:16:14,300 --> 01:16:18,600
I'll take any man wants to kick the shite
out of the Japs and the Huns.

997
01:16:20,000 --> 01:16:23,800
That's it, pack your gear.
We're going to war, gentlemen!

998
01:16:30,600 --> 01:16:32,400
<i>She had left a note.</i>

999
01:16:33,800 --> 01:16:36,500
<i>She wrote,</i>
<i>"It was nice to have met you."</i>

1000
01:16:37,300 --> 01:16:38,900
<i>And that was it.</i>

1001
01:16:42,100 --> 01:16:45,200
<i>It wasn't the war any of us expected.</i>

1002
01:16:45,300 --> 01:16:48,900
<i>We would just tow crippled ships,</i>
<i>scraps of metal, really.</i>

1003
01:16:49,500 --> 01:16:52,500
<i>If there was a war, we didn't see it.</i>

1004
01:16:54,400 --> 01:16:58,500
<i>There was a man assigned to us.</i>
<i>The Chief Gunner loved the Navy.</i>

1005
01:16:58,600 --> 01:17:00,800
<i>But most of all, he loved America.</i>

1006
01:17:00,900 --> 01:17:03,800
There is no other country in the world.

1007
01:17:03,900 --> 01:17:05,000
When you spell America...

1008
01:17:05,100 --> 01:17:09,200
<i>His name was Dennis Smith,</i>
<i>and he was a full-blooded Cherokee.</i>

1009
01:17:09,300 --> 01:17:12,400
<i>His family had been Americans</i>
<i>for over 500 years.</i>

1010
01:17:12,500 --> 01:17:17,100
These pacifists.
They say they won't fight on conscience.

1011
01:17:17,200 --> 01:17:20,800
Now, where would be
if everybody decided to act

1012
01:17:20,900 --> 01:17:24,800
- according to their conscience?
- Keep it down, would you, Chief?

1013
01:17:41,100 --> 01:17:44,400
Hey. I've been watching you.

1014
01:17:45,600 --> 01:17:47,400
You seem trustworthy.

1015
01:17:49,200 --> 01:17:51,300
If something happens to me,

1016
01:17:55,400 --> 01:17:57,900
could you see that this gets to my wife?

1017
01:17:58,100 --> 01:18:02,600
<i>He'd given me all of his pay.</i>
<i>Hadn't spent a dime of it.</i>

1018
01:18:04,500 --> 01:18:07,800
I want my family to know
I was thinking about them.

1019
01:18:12,500 --> 01:18:14,400
All hands on deck!

1020
01:18:16,900 --> 01:18:19,700
Get your asses up here,
you lazy bastards!

1021
01:18:41,000 --> 01:18:43,200
<i>The war had finally found us.</i>

1022
01:18:45,900 --> 01:18:47,300
All stop!

1023
01:18:50,100 --> 01:18:52,100
Pleasant, man that light.

1024
01:19:00,000 --> 01:19:04,100
<i>A transport carrying 1,300 men</i>
<i>had been split by a torpedo.</i>

1025
01:19:06,500 --> 01:19:08,800
<i>We were first to arrive at the scene.</i>

1026
01:19:08,900 --> 01:19:12,500
- Cut the engines!
- All stop!

1027
01:19:17,600 --> 01:19:19,500
<i>We were the only sound.</i>

1028
01:19:33,500 --> 01:19:34,900
Fellas!

1029
01:19:44,800 --> 01:19:45,900
Sub!

1030
01:19:50,700 --> 01:19:53,500
We sure as hell
can't outrun them fuckers.

1031
01:19:55,200 --> 01:19:57,500
Battle stations!

1032
01:20:07,400 --> 01:20:08,400
Thank you, Chief.

1033
01:20:10,700 --> 01:20:11,800
What?

1034
01:20:24,800 --> 01:20:26,600
Is that the last one?

1035
01:21:48,400 --> 01:21:49,700
Captain!

1036
01:22:05,300 --> 01:22:07,900
They shot the hell out of my painting!

1037
01:22:09,200 --> 01:22:11,000
Give me your other hand.

1038
01:22:16,400 --> 01:22:17,400
You'll be all right, Captain.

1039
01:22:17,600 --> 01:22:21,800
They got a nice spot in Heaven
waiting for you. Nice spot.

1040
01:22:23,400 --> 01:22:26,400
You can be as mad as a mad dog
at the way things went.

1041
01:22:29,400 --> 01:22:33,100
You could swear, curse the Fates.

1042
01:22:35,400 --> 01:22:37,500
But when it comes to the end,

1043
01:22:39,700 --> 01:22:41,400
you have to let go.

1044
01:22:48,500 --> 01:22:49,700
Captain?

1045
01:23:10,500 --> 01:23:13,800
Thirteen hundred and twenty eight men
died that day.

1046
01:23:16,100 --> 01:23:19,400
I said my goodbyes to the Cherokee,
Dennis Smith.

1047
01:23:20,300 --> 01:23:23,500
John Grimm, who was right,
he was gonna die there.

1048
01:23:25,100 --> 01:23:27,700
I sent Pleasant Curtis' wife his money.

1049
01:23:28,600 --> 01:23:31,700
I said goodbye to the twin, Vic Brody,

1050
01:23:31,800 --> 01:23:36,400
and to Mike Clark,
captain of the tugboat Chelsea.

1051
01:23:38,900 --> 01:23:43,400
I said goodbye to all the other men
who had dreams of their own,

1052
01:23:43,500 --> 01:23:46,000
all the men
who wanted to be insurance salesmen

1053
01:23:46,100 --> 01:23:49,100
or doctors or lawyers or Indian chiefs.

1054
01:23:50,100 --> 01:23:51,900
This don't get fixed.

1055
01:23:54,000 --> 01:23:57,100
Out here, death didn't seem natural.

1056
01:24:14,100 --> 01:24:17,300
I'd never seen a hummingbird
that far out to sea.

1057
01:24:18,800 --> 01:24:20,400
Before or since.

1058
01:24:26,200 --> 01:24:32,400
And in May of 1945,
when I was 26 years old,

1059
01:24:32,400 --> 01:24:33,500
I came home.

1060
01:24:34,400 --> 01:24:37,000
I'm ready! I'm ready!

1061
01:24:37,100 --> 01:24:38,500
I'm coming!

1062
01:24:39,400 --> 01:24:43,000
- I'm ready!
- All right, I'm coming, Miss Alfalina.

1063
01:24:43,100 --> 01:24:44,600
- Queenie?
- Yes?

1064
01:24:50,500 --> 01:24:56,400
Sweet Jesus! Oh, you're home!
Oh, Lord, you came back!

1065
01:24:57,300 --> 01:24:59,300
- Let me look at you.
- Who's that, Mama?

1066
01:24:59,400 --> 01:25:02,600
- Child, it's your brother, Benjamin.
- I didn't know he was my brother.

1067
01:25:02,700 --> 01:25:04,400
There's a shitload of things
you don't know, child.

1068
01:25:04,500 --> 01:25:05,700
Get on out there and finish sweeping.

1069
01:25:05,800 --> 01:25:07,900
Come here, wash your hands,
help me with the table. Go on, now.

1070
01:25:08,000 --> 01:25:11,900
Turn around.
You look like you've been born again.

1071
01:25:12,000 --> 01:25:14,300
Younger than the springtime.

1072
01:25:14,400 --> 01:25:18,000
I think that preacher laid hands on you
gave you a second life.

1073
01:25:18,100 --> 01:25:21,800
I knew it that moment I saw you,
you were special.

1074
01:25:21,900 --> 01:25:23,700
I tell you what, my knees are sore,

1075
01:25:23,900 --> 01:25:26,400
'cause I've been on them every night
asking the Lord,

1076
01:25:26,500 --> 01:25:30,200
I said,
"God, just bring him home safely."

1077
01:25:30,300 --> 01:25:32,800
Remember what I told you?

1078
01:25:32,900 --> 01:25:34,600
"You never know
what's coming for you"?

1079
01:25:34,700 --> 01:25:36,600
That's right. Sit down.

1080
01:25:38,000 --> 01:25:42,100
Well, you learn anything
worth repeating?

1081
01:25:44,200 --> 01:25:48,400
- I sure saw some things.
- Oh, you seen some pain.

1082
01:25:49,900 --> 01:25:52,700
- Some joy, too?
- Sure. Sure, I did.

1083
01:25:52,800 --> 01:25:56,900
Yeah, that's what I want to hear.
Look at you.

1084
01:25:57,000 --> 01:26:00,500
- Where's Tizzy?
- Oh, baby.

1085
01:26:03,000 --> 01:26:06,900
Mr. Weathers died in his sleep
one night last April.

1086
01:26:07,000 --> 01:26:10,400
- Mama, I'm so sorry.
- Don't you worry about that, baby.

1087
01:26:12,200 --> 01:26:14,800
Yeah, well, it's only
one or two of them left now.

1088
01:26:14,900 --> 01:26:16,400
They all just about new.

1089
01:26:16,500 --> 01:26:20,400
Guess they're waiting their turn
like everybody else, huh?

1090
01:26:20,500 --> 01:26:23,200
I'm so glad you're back home with me!

1091
01:26:23,300 --> 01:26:26,400
Now, we're gonna have to find you
a wife and a new job! That's right.

1092
01:26:26,500 --> 01:26:28,400
Come on in here,
help me with this table.

1093
01:26:31,600 --> 01:26:33,200
Benjamin.

1094
01:26:33,300 --> 01:26:36,400
You're wasting your time, baby.
She's stone deaf.

1095
01:26:36,500 --> 01:26:40,600
Oh, and you'll be staying in
what was Mrs. DeSeroux's old room.

1096
01:26:40,700 --> 01:26:43,600
You're too big to be rooming
with anybody else.

1097
01:26:47,700 --> 01:26:50,300
It's a funny thing about coming home.

1098
01:26:51,000 --> 01:26:54,700
Looks the same,
smells the same, feels the same.

1099
01:26:57,500 --> 01:27:01,300
Did I ever tell you I've been struck
by lightning seven times?

1100
01:27:03,000 --> 01:27:06,400
Once when I was sitting in my truck,
just minding my own business.

1101
01:27:12,300 --> 01:27:15,700
You realize what's changed is you.

1102
01:27:18,400 --> 01:27:22,400
And late one morning,
not long after I'd been back...

1103
01:27:22,800 --> 01:27:24,100
Thank you.

1104
01:27:46,200 --> 01:27:47,300
Hey.

1105
01:27:51,900 --> 01:27:55,700
- Excuse me, is Queenie here?
- Daisy?

1106
01:27:59,500 --> 01:28:03,100
- It's me, Benjamin.
- Benjamin?

1107
01:28:06,800 --> 01:28:08,800
Oh, my God!

1108
01:28:10,100 --> 01:28:14,000
Of course it's you! Benjamin!

1109
01:28:16,100 --> 01:28:19,000
How are you?
It's been such a long time.

1110
01:28:19,100 --> 01:28:21,800
There's so much I want to know.
When did you get back?

1111
01:28:21,900 --> 01:28:23,300
Well, I got back a few weeks ago.

1112
01:28:23,400 --> 01:28:27,400
I spoke to Queenie, she said you were
in the war, somewhere at sea.

1113
01:28:27,500 --> 01:28:31,300
- We were so, so worried about you.
- Oh, I'm okay.

1114
01:28:31,400 --> 01:28:35,200
Well, look at you. You're so lovely.

1115
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:38,800
You stopped writing.

1116
01:28:40,900 --> 01:28:46,000
"When I had left, she was a girl.
And a woman had taken her place.

1117
01:28:46,400 --> 01:28:49,500
"She was the most beautiful woman
I'd ever seen."

1118
01:28:49,600 --> 01:28:51,000
Beautiful.

1119
01:28:53,200 --> 01:28:55,000
"The most beautiful."

1120
01:28:56,800 --> 01:28:58,500
- You remember Grandma Fuller?
- Why, sure I do.

1121
01:28:58,600 --> 01:29:01,700
- She passed.
- I heard that. I'm sorry.

1122
01:29:01,800 --> 01:29:06,400
I just can't believe we're both here.
Must be fate.

1123
01:29:06,500 --> 01:29:08,400
No, no, what do they call it?

1124
01:29:08,500 --> 01:29:09,900
Kismet.

1125
01:29:10,000 --> 01:29:11,900
Do you know about Edgar Cayce,
the psychic?

1126
01:29:12,000 --> 01:29:13,000
I don't believe I...

1127
01:29:13,100 --> 01:29:16,000
He says
that everything is predetermined,

1128
01:29:16,100 --> 01:29:19,500
but I like to think of it as fate.

1129
01:29:22,700 --> 01:29:25,900
I'm not sure how it works,
but I'm glad it happened.

1130
01:29:26,000 --> 01:29:29,600
Have you been to Manhattan?
It's right across the river from me.

1131
01:29:29,700 --> 01:29:31,900
Now, I can see
the Empire State Building

1132
01:29:32,000 --> 01:29:33,700
if I stand on my bed.

1133
01:29:33,800 --> 01:29:35,800
What about you?
Where have you been?

1134
01:29:35,900 --> 01:29:39,500
Tell me everything. Last time you wrote,
you said you'd been to Russia.

1135
01:29:39,600 --> 01:29:43,800
I've always wanted to go to Russia.
Is it as cold as they say?

1136
01:29:43,900 --> 01:29:46,700
- Twice as cold.
- My goodness.

1137
01:29:47,300 --> 01:29:51,900
We always said you were different.
But I think you really are.

1138
01:29:54,100 --> 01:29:57,600
You wrote that you met somebody.
Did it work out?

1139
01:29:58,100 --> 01:29:59,800
It ran its course.

1140
01:30:01,100 --> 01:30:03,200
Hey, do you remember this?

1141
01:30:14,100 --> 01:30:16,800
"This is the picture
of Old Man Kangaroo

1142
01:30:16,900 --> 01:30:19,000
"at 5:00 in the afternoon."

1143
01:30:20,800 --> 01:30:23,000
Would you like to have dinner?

1144
01:30:30,500 --> 01:30:33,400
Did I tell you
that I danced for Balanchine?

1145
01:30:34,100 --> 01:30:38,600
Oh, he's a famous choreographer.
He said that I had perfect line.

1146
01:30:40,400 --> 01:30:44,900
You know, in a rehearsal once,
a dancer fell.

1147
01:30:45,000 --> 01:30:47,800
And he just...
He just put it right into the production.

1148
01:30:47,900 --> 01:30:51,400
I mean, can you imagine that?
Like in a... In a classical ballet?

1149
01:30:51,500 --> 01:30:54,700
You know, a dancer,
intentionally falling.

1150
01:30:54,800 --> 01:30:58,500
There's a whole new word
for dance now. It's called "abstract."

1151
01:30:58,600 --> 01:30:59,900
No, he's not the only one, though.

1152
01:31:00,000 --> 01:31:03,900
There's Lincoln Kirstein
and Lucia Chase, and oh, my...

1153
01:31:04,000 --> 01:31:06,500
Oh, there's Agnes de Mille.

1154
01:31:06,600 --> 01:31:08,700
She's just torn up all those conventions,

1155
01:31:08,800 --> 01:31:10,800
you know,
all that straight-up-and-down stuff.

1156
01:31:10,900 --> 01:31:14,100
It's not about the formality of the dance,
it's about what the dancer's feeling.

1157
01:31:14,200 --> 01:31:16,900
As she told me
about this big new world,

1158
01:31:17,000 --> 01:31:19,500
names that didn't mean a thing to me,

1159
01:31:19,600 --> 01:31:21,600
I didn't really hear very much
of what she was saying.

1160
01:31:21,700 --> 01:31:24,000
It's new and it's modern
and it's American.

1161
01:31:24,100 --> 01:31:27,200
They understand our vigor
and our physicality.

1162
01:31:27,300 --> 01:31:29,500
Oh, my God.
I've just been talking and talking.

1163
01:31:29,700 --> 01:31:34,100
No, no, I've enjoyed listening.
I didn't know you smoked.

1164
01:31:34,200 --> 01:31:35,700
I'm old enough.

1165
01:31:39,100 --> 01:31:41,600
I'm old enough for a lot of things.

1166
01:31:44,500 --> 01:31:47,000
In New York, we stay up all night,

1167
01:31:48,200 --> 01:31:51,000
watch the sun come up
over the warehouses.

1168
01:31:53,400 --> 01:31:55,700
There's always something to do.

1169
01:32:13,400 --> 01:32:15,500
I have to go back tomorrow.

1170
01:32:16,600 --> 01:32:18,800
- So soon.
- Wish I could stay.

1171
01:32:23,600 --> 01:32:26,700
Dancers don't need costumes
or scenery anymore.

1172
01:32:26,800 --> 01:32:30,400
I can imagine
dancing completely naked.

1173
01:32:31,700 --> 01:32:34,000
Have you read D.H. Lawrence?

1174
01:32:34,100 --> 01:32:36,200
- Well...
- His books were banned.

1175
01:32:36,400 --> 01:32:39,900
The words are like making love.

1176
01:33:24,400 --> 01:33:29,000
In our company,
we have to trust each other.

1177
01:33:34,300 --> 01:33:38,000
Sex is a part of it.

1178
01:33:42,400 --> 01:33:45,300
You know,
a lot of the dancers are lesbians.

1179
01:33:47,500 --> 01:33:50,500
There was one woman
who wanted to sleep with me.

1180
01:33:57,900 --> 01:34:00,900
- Does that upset you?
- Which part?

1181
01:34:02,000 --> 01:34:04,400
Somebody wanting to sleep with me.

1182
01:34:04,900 --> 01:34:06,100
You're a desirable woman.

1183
01:34:06,200 --> 01:34:09,900
I would think most of them
would want to sleep with you.

1184
01:34:10,000 --> 01:34:12,100
Let's go back to the house.

1185
01:34:13,100 --> 01:34:15,500
Or we could get a room somewhere.

1186
01:34:18,500 --> 01:34:21,600
- We could lay down your jacket.
- I don't know, Daisy.

1187
01:34:21,800 --> 01:34:27,100
It's not that I wouldn't like to or anything.
I think I'll just disappoint you.

1188
01:34:28,000 --> 01:34:31,100
Oh, Benjamin, I've been with older men.

1189
01:34:31,900 --> 01:34:33,900
You're going back to New York
in the morning.

1190
01:34:34,000 --> 01:34:36,300
You should be with your friends.

1191
01:34:37,300 --> 01:34:39,800
- You're only young once.
- Oh, I'm old enough.

1192
01:34:39,900 --> 01:34:42,500
Daisy, just not tonight, is all.

1193
01:34:56,100 --> 01:34:58,200
We could go hear some music.

1194
01:35:00,500 --> 01:35:03,200
Our lives are defined by opportunities.

1195
01:35:04,000 --> 01:35:06,000
Even the ones we miss.

1196
01:35:06,900 --> 01:35:10,500
You look so handsome
and so distinguished.

1197
01:35:10,600 --> 01:35:12,800
They're saying the hurricane's
gonna miss us, blow right on by.

1198
01:35:12,900 --> 01:35:17,500
- Oh, that's great.
- I'll stay under the blankets with Mother.

1199
01:35:17,600 --> 01:35:21,700
She says nothing... Benjamin?

1200
01:35:23,600 --> 01:35:24,700
"Things were becoming different..."

1201
01:35:24,800 --> 01:35:25,900
... for me.

1202
01:35:26,100 --> 01:35:29,600
My hair had very little gray
and grew like weeds.

1203
01:35:29,800 --> 01:35:33,500
My sense of smell was keener.
My hearing, more acute.

1204
01:35:33,600 --> 01:35:36,300
I could walk further and faster.

1205
01:35:36,400 --> 01:35:42,100
While everybody else was aging,
I was getting younger, all alone.

1206
01:35:45,200 --> 01:35:46,400
Come in.

1207
01:35:47,800 --> 01:35:49,100
Benjamin.

1208
01:35:50,100 --> 01:35:53,300
- Do you remember me?
- Well, sure I do, Mr. Button.

1209
01:35:54,000 --> 01:35:57,600
- What happened to you?
- Darn foot. Got infected, so...

1210
01:35:59,300 --> 01:36:00,500
Welcome home, my friend.

1211
01:36:03,200 --> 01:36:06,300
I see you're still drinking
your Sazerac with whiskey.

1212
01:36:06,400 --> 01:36:07,600
Creature of habit.

1213
01:36:07,700 --> 01:36:09,800
You still visiting the house
on Bourbon Street?

1214
01:36:09,900 --> 01:36:11,700
Not for a long time.

1215
01:36:13,300 --> 01:36:15,400
Interesting times, though.

1216
01:36:15,500 --> 01:36:19,900
We went from making 40,000
to nearly half a million buttons a day.

1217
